description.text:
Zippy 2.0 is a 3D printed Arduino Nano based balancing robot with a custom PCB.

The frame can be printed in multiple colors by pausing the print at the right height and switching filament. The SketchUp 2017 file is included for design customization. The frame is put together with a few dozen M3x10mm bolts and hex nuts, and four M3 standoffs for the PCB. I printed the frame in PLA with a 0.2mm layer height and 40% infill.

I've also included an optional set of bumpers, which can protect Zippy in the event of a fall. Wrap the bumpers with pipe insulation tubes for a little extra cushion. Yes, the bumpers detract from Zippy's graceful physique, but make Zippy a little more rugged for kids.

The code and circuit design can be found on my GitHub site at:
https://github.com/elkayem/ZippyTheBalancingRobot

The PCB is optional, but yields a more compact design than a hand-soldered protoboard. The original prototype version was put together on a breadboard with lots of jumper wires. This is certainly a great way to get started. The STMicroelectronics 8A motor drivers do not come in a convenient package for breadboarding, but ST does provide evaluation boards which work well with a prototype system. The PCB does require some SMD work and an additional outlay for PCB manufacture (I ordered 10 boards from China for less than $2 a board). Even with the fine 0.5 mm pitch, the drivers can be hand soldered to the board (I did!) with a steady hand and patience. There are plenty of YouTube videos on how to do this.

Here are the important parts for Zippy 2.0:

  • 2 x VNH5180A motor drivers
  • (Optional) Zippy printed circuit board (see Eagle files)
  • 2 x 30:1 Metal Gearmotor 37Dx68L mm with 64 CPR Encoder from Pololu
  • GY-521 MPU-6050 gyro/accelerometer breakout board
  • Arduino Nano
  • ZIPPY (Of course!) Flightmax 3000mAh 3S 20C LiPo battery
  • 16x2 character LCD display
  • Remote control with PWM receiver
  • Two Schottky diodes (I used Fairchild SB1245 12A diodes)
  • Various resistors, capacitors, 10K trimpot, pushbutton, connectors (see schematic)

I've also included a schematic in the Eagle folder. Gerber files are provided in the Eagle folder if ordering from a PCB manufacturer. Otherwise, use a breadboard and wire according to the enclosed schematic.

Pay close attention to polarity on motor wheels (swapping motor leads as necessary) and MPU-6050 orientation. The software assumes the gyro/accelerometer is mounted with the +X axis facing the front of the robot.

Depending on your robot inertia, the PID gains may need to be retuned. Increase as needed to achieve crisp response without any oscillation.

Check out Zippy 2.0 in action: https://youtu.be/0io5SwitLzY

description.text:
A simple mount to attach a phone to your guitar. The mount keeps your phone in place to view lyrics, sheet music, tablature, or any other material hands-free while you play. When not in use it folds down and out of the way. Can also be used in any other environment where a simple collapsing 90-degree mount may be wanted.

Attaches using adhesive strips. Requires a bolt at least 45mm long with a maximum shaft diameter of 4mm, as well as a matching nut. A locknut is preferred, and washers are recommended.

This was designed to fit my iPhone 7 w/ case, which has a width of 70mm. To scale this to fit any other phone, simply measure the width of your device and compare the measurement to that. For example:

If your phone has a width of 60mm, divide 60 by 70 to get ~0.857, which means you will need to scale the model by 85.7% in order to fit your device.

I can provide some custom sizes by request, but I obviously cannot accommodate every device size.

Just a nice ratchet for holding your misc. cables together.

This is my second ratchet design iteration. The previous ones required some assembly and M3 nut & bolt but in this one the single STL file contains both parts preassembled so you don't need to join them after the print.
I left 0.3 mm gaps between the parts and printed from PLA with 0.2 mm layer height, without any support. The result is so fantastic I'll continue use this pre-assembled methodology in my future designs!
I printed it on my Prusa i3 MK2 which did not get the multi-extruder upgrade yet but to bow before the father of my wonderful printer I rendered an image where the lock mechanism is Prusa-orange :)
If you hate noisy bulky keys as much as I do then this design is for you.

  • 2 pcs M5 nyloc nuts

I printed a spacer to use the stock extruder head bracket but it rattled so I made this. I recommend .2mm layers with 15% infill WITH SUPPORTS but no raft. You can use a raft if you like but a healthy spray of Aquanet Unscented Super Hold allows me to print this part with supports without the use of a raft.  
I hate rafts and supports but supports are a necessary evil with this print because if I made the filament tube guide a solid block, it would collide with the X-axis rod.   
Be sure to remove the supports under/inside the filament tube guide, under the clamps and in the wiring gap.  
(Assuming you have already removed the left fan, left heat sink and left stepper)  
Remove the stock head and snip the right filament,remove the right filament tube guide (and any spacers you may have inserted).

title: Geeetech Prusa I3X Y-Axis Cableslide for PCB MK2a heatbed cable

description.text:
This is my second created thing.

It is created with thinkercad.

I had a problem with the cable of the heatbed, i gets cought by the acrylic frame of the Geeetech I3X and pulls on the heatbed.

It is so designed, that you can use the original screws from the Y-axis motor mount.
You only need to release the tension of the Y-axis belt and unscrew the 2 screws which hold the motorbracket. Put the screws trough the holes from the slide and screw them back in. Now tension the belt again and you are done.

I went with raft because of the glassbed. It is printed with 0,3 mm nozzle, 0,2 mm layer hight and 100% infill. If you print it as seen on the picture, you will need no support.

comments.text:
I've bounced it off a fair few things so far and tried drilling it into the ground at the flying field too (not deliberately tho!) and all I got was one arm started to detach on a couple of layers.
Have printed a new one but made it 1mm thicker to provide more space between the motor screws and the windings on the coils as I had a problem with them touching, and printed at 50% infill - so far it seems to have fought off concrete posts, a wall and the patio slabs 3 times without damage!
Will be getting some more practice in soon then possibly I'll try it without the prop guards to save some weight.

description.text:
This is 4 years of development condensed down into this thing. We developed this printer to be fast, accurate and reliable at the same time while still beeing cheap to buy.
As we're loving the idea of sharing all we have with the community we open sourced all the files for everyone.

Main Features:

  • Auto bed leveling
  • fast, accurate and reliable printing
  • easy accessable Heated bed
  • powered by core xy with fishing line
  • internal power supply
  • opensource
  • many upgrades possible
  • compatible with e3D v6 and e3D Volcano

So what will you need to build this pinter?
You can buy the full kit here: https://3dator.com/en/shop/3dator-kit/
Or buy all parts on your own:
http://wiki.3dator.com/index.php/BOM/en

After you got all parts see how it is put together here: http://wiki.3dator.com/index.php/Bauanleitung/en

If you want to do your own customisations have a look at our git repo which also includes step files:
https://github.com/3Dator/3dator

Keep sharing what you've done with your 3Dator with #3Dator. We'd love to see it.

Changelog:
19.06.2017 updated endstop_holder
22.06.2017 fixed bug in printhead (missing holes)
11.07.2017 fixed bug in both xy_motor_carrier files

Printer:

3Dator

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The Extruder works better if you are printing the extruder base with 0.1 mm layers.

More details instuctions can be found here: http://wiki.3dator.com/index.php/3Dator_Selbstbau/en

Upgrades you can buy or build youself:
find the files in our other things or on github: https://github.com/3Dator/3dator_mods

  • E3D nozzle and Extruder
  • use BL Touch bed probe
  • filament switch that pauses print when filament is empty
  • pcb plotter addon
  • raspberry pi upgrade with camera
  • rubber feed for noise reduction
  • y adapter for easy two color printhing
  • real dual extruder upgrade

Planned upgrades:

  • Flow sensor
  • viscous material extruder
  • closed build chamber
  • filtration system

title: Printable Pocket Butterfly Comb (modified from techno246's version)

description.text:
I downloaded the original files from "Printable Pocket Butterfly Comb" by techno246, whom I think is the original designer of this model. However, there're several problems with the comb, so I re-drew the comb to fix them. Here's a list of the things that I changed: Pins & Caps:
The original design requires additional fasteners. Since I'm having problem finding the right size and didn't want to bother buying a whole bunch, I just went ahead and drew some pins and caps for it. Just stick the pin through the holes and snap the cap on it from the other end. It's supposed to be perfect match, so it might not fit if there're burrs on the pin or in the hole. Use a small filer or sand paper to remove the burrs and it should fit right in. For some unknown reason, the size of the pins and caps don't always come out right on my printing software. In case is this happens to you as well, you can easily build them in any 3D CAD software. The pin has a diameter of 2.5mm (so does the hole in the cap), and the gap between two caps is 10mm. I use 6mm for diameter and 2mm for thickness of the caps, and I put a 1.5mm fillet at the end of the caps. Therefore, the pin itself should have a length of 12mm (not including the cap on the pin) because 2mm of it needs to go into the hole of the hollow cap. I hope this makes sense to whoever needs to build it. If not, please leave me comments so I can try explaining it better. Comb:

  • The original comb was way too loose, so I changed the thickness from 2mm to 3mm. This stops the comb from shaking around while I actually use it to brush my hair. However, the tightness might cause the spinning to be not as smooth, so I file down all the burrs on the handle then put a little bit of vaseline around the joints, and it works perfectly. Afterall, what's the point of making a butterfly comb if it doesn't spin smoothly?

  • I made the teeth longer (from 10mm to 12mm) since all of my friends are complaining about the teeth being too short. Apparently the additional 2mm made it more functional being a comb.

  • I also made the comb a little bit longer (about 5mm longer) since there were still plenty of rooms in the handle while the comb was in closed position. This modification allows me to add 3 more teeth to the comb.

  • The bottom of the comb has parts sticking out on both sides for unknown reason. I could not find any purpose to that design, so I removed it while I re-drew the comb.

  • At the end, I decided to add a 1mm fillet around the comb. There's no critical purpose to that modification, only I happened to feel that it might look a little more classy this way.
    • Handle:
    I did not make any change to the handle since it is already perfect as it is. The original design can be found by the link below. Thank techno246 for the wonderful design. I had a lot fun playing with it, and my frinds all liked it. Printable Pocket Butterfly Comb (by techno246)
    https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15895 BTW, this is my first upload on Thingiverse since I just recently bought my first 3D printer. I hope people would like my modification to this butterfly comb. Please leave me comments, and I wish everyone has fun playing with it. Have a nice day!

• Print 1 comb, 2 handles, 2 pins & 2 caps.
  • File down all the burrs (especially on the handles) so the comb will spin smoothly.
  • Assemble the comb and handles. Use the pins to hold them together, then snap the caps to the end of the pins.
    • That's it! Have fun playing with it and show it to your friends. (Chances are that they will ask you to print one for them.)

title: Star Wars Keychain | Tinkercad Import Lesson

description.text: A Thingiverse search for "star wars keychain" brings up a couple results but they have some small flaws (too flimsy, hole not positioned well, etc.) I'm trying to fix those issues with this simple design. The keychain looks best printed in multiple colors (If your printer allows pauses, switch out the filament color once it starts printing the logo.) May the 4th be with you!
CCSS

Originally this was just a quick, fun little project for Star Wars day. However, I then realized that many students may not know about the Import feature of Tinkercad, and it could make a great learning experience. This lesson assumes students have been introduced to the basics of Tinkercad. The focus of this lesson is to:
a) learn to vectorize images
b) use the Tinkercad Import feature
c) design a keychain around their chosen artwork I'll be using the Star Wars logo as an example, however, students may use any clip art or logo of their choosing.

Step 1: Choose an Image Do a quick google image search for whatever you're going to include on your keychain. Usually a logo or clipart is best, so try including those words in your search. For more precise results, try using the "tools" tab to search for transparent images, and large ones with a high resolution. Then choose and download your image as a .jpg or .png. Search for your image Set to Here's the logo I chose Step 2: Vectorize Now you'll take your downloaded .jpg or .png and convert it to a vector image (.svg.), since a vector is the only type of image file Tinkercad can accept. There are a number of free online vectorizers you can use, but my favorite is https://www.vectorizer.io/ and that's what I tend to use. It has fairly good instructions and is relatively intuitive, so just follow their directions and you should be just fine. Download your converted image as an .svg. Step 3: Import Logo to Tinkercad Go to https://www.tinkercad.com/ (if you've never used Tinkercad, watch this video first: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KCaenAGeK_Q It is a bit outdated, so sorry!), open a workspace, and name it. Click the "Import" button. Import button This will open a window, asking you to choose a file. Select your .svg you created before. Then change your dimensions to something reasonable, such as 20 mm. Your logo should now be imported. Logo imported! Step 4: Design the Keychain Personally, I like to work in inches, so click "edit grid" and convert to inches. Insert a ruler somewhere into your workspace. Now we can rescale our logo to inches. I suggest making it .2" thick, and then scaling so that you keep approximately the same ratio for the sides, but no dimension is more than 2". For the Star Wars logo, 1.75" by .75" seemed best. Now we can go on to build the keychain itself. Scaling Logo Step 5: Designing the Keychain Of course, there are many ways to go about this, but here is the one I used. Insert a rectangle the size of your logo, but .1" high. Then insert a cylinder, also .1" high, with the diameter of the shorter side of your rectangle. Place the rectangle so the it is "inside" the circle, and cuts the circle in half. Then group these 2 shapes. Base keychain: only 2 shapes! Now put in a hole. Insert a cylinder with a diameter of .25" and .1" high. Place it in the rounded edge you just created and group to form a hole. (Snap grid helps with this!) Step 6: Add the Logo Finally, you can drag your logo back in and center it on your base keychain. Once again, group, and you're all finished! You just created a custom keychain with your very own image! High five! All finished!

Software Tinkercad
Slicer/Host software of your choice Physical 3d printer
Keyrings
Black and Yellow filament (preferable)

  • Image Conversion
30 minutes- 1 Hour

Dual Color Printing

Teach the students how to pause a print and switch out the filament using g-code commands in slic3r! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sk1aP6MQEhc

Negative Image

Instead of having the image extruded out of a thin keychain, try making the base keychain .2" thick and an 1/8" larger in the other directions. Change the logo to a hole, .1" thick and .1" raised from the plane. Center it in the base keychain and group!

Negative Extrude

I hope this guide was helpful! I had a blast making it and poured a bunch of time into it, so please support me by liking it, and upload your own designs as remixes. Thanks for checking it out, and happy Star Wars day!

title: Mount for ESCs and receiver box on electric mountain board

description.text:
This part is intended for holding the speed controllers (ESCs) and water-proof receiver box in place on an electric mountain board.

The setup of the eMTB is quite standard (Trampa Holypro 35), Hobbywing MAX6 ESCs, and a receiver box (Traxxas 5624).

The most clean builds with these parts use a CNC shaped carbon plate for fitting the parts (https://goo.gl/CbELqQ), but it is quite expensive and has no dumping for the ESCs.

The idea here is to use velcro for the actual mounting of the parts (the strong kind - https://goo.gl/VtC9S7). The perimeter of the part is raised so the velcro does not show (After installing it I see that it doesn't do that actually, but it still looks good IMO)

I played with two options but printed and tested only one (the one with the ESCs on top).

A small disclaimer, I only spent a couple of hours on the board with this setup at this point, but all seems to work as planned, I'll update if that changes.

Designed using OnShape

Onshape:
ESCs on top - https://goo.gl/GDPjt7
Receiver on top - https://goo.gl/zexEEg

This is not exactly the final model, but gives an idea on the intended layout. These are the earlier attempts, I ended up printing the version with the ESCs on top, as anyway the motor mount is there, so the ESC sticking out does not show (and they are more open to air and proper wiring that way.

description.text:
This is a modular truss bridge in HO scale.
It is modular, because, as you can see in the last photo, there are two locating holes for additional sections. At the other end, there are two matching pins that allow you to align additional bridge sections perfectly.
There is a walkway on the left side (what I call the left side) with a safety handrailing....which I should have printed in yellow, but didn't think of it til afterwards, lol...and this is supported from underneath, as shown in the photo.
Print time: around 4 hours at the given settings.

Commercial use is not allowed.

Anet A8 prusa clone

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

.2mm

15%

Notes:

No supports needed.
Raft not needed.
I printed at .2 resolution, but .25 works ok too.
Print 3 of the top girder middle.
Will fit on 2 gcode files for a 200 x 200 bed.
Stl files have all been run through netfabb (hence they all have "fixed" in their name) and should be printed in the orientation of the stl file/

Post printing.

Recommended painting after assembly (for gluing reasons) unless you plan on painting parts different colours.
Should be no, or very little clean up required, except maybe a slight reaming out of the locating holes.
Note: the 2 end post and the middle post on the hand railing are longer than the rest. These 3 fit in the corresponding holes along the edge of the walkway.

title: Lasercut shrink tube organizer system with integrated cutter

description.text:
This is a lasercut, stackable organizing system for things like shrink tube or small wire with an integrated cutter. It uses normal utility blades.
It's designed to fit a wide variety of reels up to:
diameter: 145 mm
width: 60 mm
Shrink tube reels from Reichelt are usually a perfect fit: http://fablink.de/3w

Cut from 4mm plywood/mdf and glue the pieces together.
The bottom piece has small cutouts for the stacking pins. Make shure you orient it correctly.
Be careful at the top near the hinge not to glue the lid down. Also remember to put the lid in before you glue the last sidepanel on.
Use m3 screws to hold down the blade and align the cutting edge to go from the inner edge of the 45° angle to approx. half way of the blade-protection thing.
You can also zip-tie multiple boxes together sideways by using the slots at the back under the hinge and at the front on the protruding part of the sidepanel.

description.text:
While printing some toys for my kids I broke the ABS idler arm on my Prusa Clone. I hated it for a while so this made me have to design and print a new one. I'm pretty sure my kit is an i3 rework, but just to be safe check the threaded rod distance before hand; should be roughly 32mm from outside to outside.

The files are NOT ORIENTED to the BED. Make sure to rotate to the best position.

The screw trap in the idler arm is designed to be a snug press in fit but loose once fully inserted.

Do not over tighten the screw that holds in the idler pulley as it will cause more friction in your motion than you want. Use a drop of thread locker and tighten until their is 1 to 2 threads coming out of the nut.

Here are some hydraulic fitting plugs & caps to fit US Dash -12 & JIC fittings .
They were primarily designed for capping dry sump lines on NASCAR engines during Engine removal & fitment & include a standard -12 plug & cap & also a long Cap for sump Scavenge line filters . They can also be used for general hydraulic systems .
They are obviously NOT for operating pressures , just to plug the lines & stop a mess during service work. Similar units are available from hydraulic outlets , but they are very thin plastic & general deform easy & jump threads when tightening & often don't seal too well. These printable parts are solid ( depending on your infill %) & a are much stronger & can be tightened to much higher torques so they seal better . These were designed for ABS , so depending of your printer & filament & shrinkage rates , you may need to make slight scale adjustments prior to printing.

Had issues with the home made keypad so make this second front panel (Top Half V2) which takes the Numeric Keypad from Maplin (http://www.maplin.co.uk/numeric-press-button-keypad-220344). It interfaces with the alarm the same way. Also I had issues with the LED's which stood off of the PCB. They broke the tracks so I also moved them to the side of the box to be better seen through the shed door's window. A friend of mine wanted to have an alarm on his shed/garage. He had brought one but it failed to work correctly after about a year. He then asked me if I would be able to create him a simple little system to help protect his stuff. This is the result of that request. It has two circuits, one for PIRs and another for door switches. Run by a 4 digit code to turn the alarm on and off, internal and external sounders/alarms. In the picture the base of the case is two tone, this was due to me running out of filament through the print and inserting a new (different colour) filament while it was still printing. It is only meant to be printed one colour, no dualstruder needed!

The system is built around the Arduino. I had a rubber top from a keypad which I used for the pin entry. It needed a custom PCB to run (has those little conductive pads on the back of each key). It is wired up as a standard matrix keypad so can be replaced with a similar off the shelf keypad.
I have included the STLs for the case as well as a SketchUp file if you wanted to modify it to take a normal keypad. The circuit diagram is included as well as the PCB. The case has stand-offs for the PCB's that line up with the holes in the actual board. I used M3x6mm self-tapping screws to secure the PCBs to the case and the two halves of the case.
The case bottom has slots for attaching to a wall, but the holes where the heads of the screws go to attach the halves together will need to be reamed out.
The keypad attaches to the 6 pads to the left of the ATmega, top 3 columns, bottom 3 rows. It only uses 1-9 for number input as I originally planned to use a 9 button keypad that was made with keyboard switches. The Sketch can be altered to use the final row, although the PCB would need adjusting. I included a FTDI header using the layout Sparkfun use for their FTDI-USB cables.
I have included the instruction PDF I wrote for my friend which goes through wiring, connectors and LEDs.
Wasn't going to put this up, but someone might be able to use it or get inspiration from it.
Basic screwdriver-type handle with a quadrant driver.

[Note: I ended up printing it by flipping the model vertically and sinking it 3.5mm down into the bed. There was a tiny bit of sagging at the top end of the handle but it printed fine without support. Neither of these changes currently exists in the uploaded model.] "Quadrant drive" is what I call this simple system of transmitting torque between parts using alternating quadrants of a circle. (I've never seen this used before so if it exists and has a name, let me know!) There are a number of advantages:
  • Strong: 50% of the material from each mating part contributes to the torque. Useful when both materials are the same strength, as in 3D printing. Allows you to transmit lots of torque for weak materials (like 3D-printed plastic).
  • Universal: almost any two quadrant drives can connect. There is no male or female side, and the diameter is largely irrelevant. You could attach a 1" diameter shaft to a 10mm diameter shaft with no adapters, for instance. Or attach two short shafts with quadrant drive to each other to easily extend it. Put it on screw heads, gears, pulleys, sprockets, shafts, hand cranks, robot wheels, etc.
  • Positive: Unlike other drives, all the mating surfaces between two parts (like a shaft and a gear, etc) are exactly perpendicular to the axis of rotation. This means that the driving or driven part can't round off if it's pushed too hard, the way most other drives can (hex/allen, Phillips, etc). The failure mode is basically all or none: either the entire thing breaks (in which case you need a stronger material or larger diameter!), or the whole thing stays intact.
  • Won't cam out like Phillips or many other drives.
    • I first machined a quadrant drive out of aluminum and some other unknown soft metal when I needed to connect a pulley to a drive shaft. I wanted it to be as strong as possible and not to deform over time. It was easy to machine. I ended up also drilling a through-hole between the parts and tapping the shaft so I could hold them together with a screw, and it worked beautifully. This approach would be very useful for things like attaching robot wheels, for instance. I'm planning on adding some other parts that use quadrant drive. Hopefully I'll get the time soon.

description.text:
So I wanted some drawers to organize my electronics stuff and I like to fool around in Fusion 360. There are lots of good drawers on Thingiverse already but I wanted to try my hand at making some because I think it's fun.

This is what I came up with. They are designed to be printed standing up which results in full control of the length of the drawers by simply telling your slicer to stop at a certain height. The bottom is 1mm thick so to get a 20mm long drawer you would stop at 21mm. The default length of the model is 200mm.

They are noted as width x height in an arbitrary unit system. The outer footprint of a 1x1 drawer is roughly 25x25mm give or take (You know, 3D printing...).
The inside of the 1x1 drawer is roughly 15x15mm. The inside of the bigger ones are a multiple of this plus some extra.

The foot part is useful to get the whole contraption off the table a little because it can be a bit fiddly to open the drawers on the bottom row due to how low the handle is located.

If you can get the perfect settings the faces can be press fitted together with relative success. I just glue mine on with some superglue. Works great.

title: Adapter Redesign for neilmig's LulzBot Mini Spool Holder

description.text:
The adapter portion from neilmig's original design wouldn't work me for two reasons:

  1. It required two longer M5 bolts than what came with the Lulzbot Mini
  2. The original hole for the 5/16" all-thread was too small; and the slant on the side was difficult to use a nut for reinforcement

In this re-mix I addressed both points. The 5/16" will now thread through with ample tension but I still used a nut at the end for additional bind. You can now re-use the factory M5 bolts (at least from the 2017 Lulzbot Mini).

For additional information, I used two skateboard bearing spacers as seen in the pictures; and used a dedicated wingnut (5/16"-18) instead of the knob for no necessary reason other than it is stronger. The spacers can probably be printed as well if you do not have any.
